no actual impacts realised to date</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-232670987.241595030be6741a</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Schools</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2011</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>Methods for analysis of non-covalent complexes were utilised in the grant. These were established and details
documented in the publications.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2012</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>9A971EB7-14AA-4C0F-B08C-BE83C27575F3</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Societal</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>545d35d96062a4.24389718</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Education,Pharmaceuticals and Medical Biotechnology</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>It has been known for more than half a century that some pathogenic bacteria (e.g. Escherichia coli and Salmonella
enterica) produce hair-like structures on their surfaces. These &amp;quot;pili&amp;quot; or &amp;quot;fimbriae&amp;quot; contain at their tip a special protein
molecule, called an adhesin, which allows the bacteria to attach to the host cell surface, thereby initiating the process of
infection. These hair-like structures are formed from the assembly of hundreds of copies of protein subunits with similar
structure into a long polymer chain linked by non-covalent interactions between each subunit that have to assemble in a
specific order in order to be functional. To make this happen, a specific chaperone is used to fold the pilus subunit into an
assembly-competent conformation and an outer membrane-embedded protein, called the usher then assembles the pilus
and pushed each subunit out of the bacteria in a specific order. The usher also serves as an anchor, tethering the pilus to
the bacterial surface, arming the bacterium for attack.
Understanding how the usher orchestrates folding of pili is fascinating, fundamental question in biology. It is also of
importance since disabling pilus assembly may provide a new route for the creation of anti-microbial compounds, much
needed in the background of the rapid evolution of antibiotic-resistant bacteria. In this project we developed novel assays
using mass spectrometry to work out how the pilus subunits assemble in such a specific manner. Two different approaches
were taken. First, we looked at the extent to which subunit assembly specificity is inherently encoded in the different amino
acid sequences found in each subunit type. We then expanded on these results to examine how the usher protein itself
brings about rapid and specific assembly. New tasks for different parts of the usher were discovered using the approach we
developed, and we were able to propose relay of hand-over-hand passing of different subunits to different parts of the
usher to bring about specific assembly. Finally, and in very exciting experiments, we used mass spectrometry to examine
the intact usher protein itself in the act of pilus assembly. This was a major feat of experimentation since the analysis of
membrane proteins using mass spectrometry, especially large protein complexes, is at the very forefront of this technology.
This work has not yet been published, but it paves the way for an analysis of pilus assembly in real time and, in the future,
could provide important information into how potential inhibitors of pilus assembly act.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>Publications, conferences and other communications</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>468E979B-A719-4ED6-8773-BDEFABA7732F</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>545d3572cd9711.88412256</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Healthcare,Pharmaceuticals and Medical Biotechnology</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>CF35C86D-B2C2-4D23-918F-C107AADA1955</gtr:id><gtr:title>The role of chaperone-subunit usher domain interactions in the mechanism of bacterial pilus biogenesis revealed by ESI-MS.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Molecular &amp; cellular proteomics : MCP</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/7470ffa17883f984cda6dca75c200ea6"><gtr:id>7470ffa17883f984cda6dca75c200ea6</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Morrissey B</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2012-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>1535-9476</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>doi_55f94b94b3ae4518</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>27852D07-39A9-45C2-8719-8F58034F59AD</gtr:id><gtr:title>Second order rate constants of donor-strand exchange reveal individual amino acid residues important in determining the subunit specificity of pilus biogenesis.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Journal of the American Society for Mass Spectrometry</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/08f2e36728fdcefa0fe43a3592434df8"><gtr:id>08f2e36728fdcefa0fe43a3592434df8</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Leney AC</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2011-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>1044-0305</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>543653fdc0b